In-trap motion of particles

I wanted to see how the particles move as the angle rotates. To do this I measured the distance traveled from their initial state. This is particular helpful since all particles start from the equilibrium position.

normalized with the trap separation. This will tell us if the particles travel the whole trap, or get stuck in the central hill.

Where I averaged across all particles and across all realizations. I also included values up to where all de interesting dynamics occur.
From here we can see that for fast rotations, the horizontal particles move from one side to the other of the trap, while the verticals move a bit, and go back to the equilibrium position.

The interesting case comes from the slow rotations. We can see that that both move a lot and vibrate up to 20 degrees, then the horizontals start to move to the other side of the trap, slowly but surely, while the verticals do not really decide what to do. Then around 40 degrees the verticals go all over the place but in average they move a lot around the central hill.

What I want to know is what happens with the forces around 20 and 40 degrees.

The standard deviation across realizations seems fine enough (see the scale)

However, the standard deviation across particles, I am not sure on how to measure count those across realizations.
Perhaps something like , the average across realizations of the deviations across traps.
Note the scale


We can see that for vertical traps the standard deviation is basically half, meaning that the particles are really all over the place. Seeing the videos, yes, a bunch of verticals cross the hill, and a bunch do not.

Angle State

Here I wanted to see a few different angles, particularly the final and initial state. But specifically the region around 40 degrees since interesting things seem to happen. If you see the video, the forces on the horizontals grow to their maximum, and then decrease after that, making it virtually impossible for the, e.g. vertices to move.

Additionally, other forces invert directions around this line.

Notes from Pietro's paper

  • How do I compute the threshold field to switch from one side to the other of the trap?
    • I could do a simulation of one vertex with a few particles and run a quench.
    • Then plot the normalized distance traveled from the initial position
    • Then we can explore the cases.
  • Transition toward the GS can be monitored in terms of the average vertex spin where is the net spin associated to the vertex. This applies to the ice rule as it minimizes the topological charges.
  • They induce a biased state by tilting the system, and then measure the usual 6-fold symmetry with the orientational correlation functions and the bond order parameter . "The transformation is martensitic-like with a homogeneous lattice deformation produced by a collective particle displacement"
Questions for future ideas.
  • In the absence of a substrate, the natural ordering of particles with isotropic interactions is the triangular lattice. What about anisotropic interactions?

How do we characterize a martensite transition in partice-based systems?

I am not sure.

In Pietro's paper, they mention collective particle displacement. Which kind of confirms what we have, but does not really tells me much. Since they compute typical quantities for 6-fold symmetry, they don't really help in a square lattice.

Summary from my extensive Wikipedia research

A diffusionless transformation, commonly known as displacive transformation, denotes solid-state alterations in crystal structures that do not hinge on the diffusion of atoms across extensive distances. Rather, these transformations manifest as a result of synchronized shifts in atomic positions, wherein atoms undergo displacements of distances smaller than the spacing between adjacent atoms, all while preserving their relative arrangement. An example of such a phenomenon is the martensitic transformation, a notable occurrence observed in the context of steel materials.

The most commonly encountered transformation of this type is the martensitic transformation, which is probably the most studied but is only one subset of non-diffusional transformations. The martensitic transformation in steel represents the most economically significant example of this category of phase transformations. However, an increasing number of alternatives, such as shape memory alloys, are becoming more important as well.

The phenomenon in which atoms or groups of atoms coordinate to displace their neighboring counterparts resulting in structural modification is known as a displacive transformation. The scope of displacive transformations is extensive, encompassing a diverse array of structural changes. As a result, additional classifications have been devised to provide a more nuanced understanding of these transformations.

Homogeneous lattice-distortive strains, also known as Bain strains, transform one Bravais lattice into a different one. This can be represented by a strain matrix which transforms one vector, , into a new vector, : These include dilation or shear.

Shuffles, aptly named, refer to the minute displacement of atoms within the unit cell. Notably, pure shuffles typically do not induce a modification in the shape of the unit cell; instead, they predominantly impact its symmetry and overall structural configuration.

And how do I measure this?

I still have no idea, I've been checking a few papers, but most of them just show it.

  • Martensitic transition in a confined colloidal suspension
    This is an old paper, and could not find a legible way to read it.

  • Nature of an Electric-Field-Induced Colloidal Martensitic Transition
    Phenomenological modeling of martensitic transitions has indeed been shown to involve terms that act as effective long-range anisotropic interactions.
    These guys basically put a bunch of colloidal particles and add an electric field to observe interactions and s-s transitions. they measure change in symmetry by a bond-order parameter

    But their martensite transformation is from one crystal structure to another. It is structural. I am not sure if we have that. Furthermore, martensite transformations always have something to do with shear stress, and I am not sure on how to relate that to our experiments.
